76561197985848071,Recommended,268650,16318891,"Posted: 11 June, 2015",all,majyst,"As a player who has over 2,400 hours into this game, i would have to say that I like it. For people who like building things this game provides an outlet to not only be creative, but to also try to put together new and interesting mechanical functions and systems.So, what is the game?Fundamentally, it is a complex vehicle designer with a focus on water based ships, and flying things which you then use to destroy other designs either in the vehicle designer, or in the massive campaign.As a new player you will first be heading to the Vehicle designer to figure out how to build something. Here you can use blocks to build the shapes of the vehicle you want. Anything from Small boats to battleships, jets to spaceships, hydrofoils, helicopters, submarines, even rudimentary ground units (Wheels and ground stuff are rumored to be improved in the future)You can mix and match as you please too, want a ship powered by large jets? Fine, go for it, its all up to your creativity.The weapon systems are also highly customizable, you dont just choose a gun from a list and smack it down on the ship, no in FTD you build the weapons block by block. Want cannon? Well do you want fast firing machine guns? That will take many auto-loaders and ammo boxes and little or no gauge increases. Want it to shoot Armor piercing rounds or Explosive? Gotta added those blocks to the gun too. Your gun knocking your ship over with each massive shell? Better add some recoil suppression to the cannon barrels.Do you like missiles? Big ones or small, fast, or slow, Fragmentation, Explosive or EMP? In the water? You bet you can make torpedoes! Mines? Check! Dumb fire bombs, Absolutly! Laser firing sharks tied to a rocket?!?!? Posi…wait, no you cant do that one, but maybe its in development.All weapon systems are modular (except simple weaopons).These systems are currentlyCannonsMissilesLasersAll of which can be customized to function in multiple ways.So, now you have your awesome first design? What do you do with it?Go play the campaign! You load onto a world named Neter where you have a tiny wooden fortress and a dinky little boats. In the campaign you gain resources by mining it in zones, so when you start you may not be able to afford your awesome boat you designed so you will have to go design a smaller cheapers boat (in campaign or in the designer)Now, you have this tiny sad little wood boat, probably with some missiles on it, what to do? Well, there 8 factions out there waiting to be destroyed or destroy you. You can control your boat yourself, or send it out to fight under the control of the ships AI, which you will need since you will have many ships in a fleet.  You are already at war with the Deep Water guard, and they are coming to get you. As you build up more resources by mining and destroying enemy ships you can in turn build up bigger ships of your own.So, now you've destroyed everything in Neter and you own the world? What do you do now?Well, a recent addition to FTD is the world Editor, here you can build your own world and your own factions to go blow up, or share the world with friends so they too can blow up YOUR world.This game has limitless potential, with a Developer who literally works WITH the community. I dont mean he reads suggestions, no he actually puts the design of enemy ships and enemy factions in the hands of the community and puts in new things based on the suggestions of the community.Give it a try, once you get the hang of it you will be rewarded over and over when you build something new and more awesome than your last creation."
,Recommended,268650,32235041,Posted: 7 June,all,pinbuck,"pros:-has what seems to be endless gameplay-you design what you want, how you want it, as long as it's practical and does the job you gave it-multiplayer ability-many main campaigns, and tons of side campaigns, and story missions-the game is complicated, and is no longer just ""bigger is better"" when creating guns, engines, etc. (in the latest version of the game)-mods are really easy to install once you get the hang of it-official game forum, where you can find mods, help, etc.http://www.fromthedepthsgame.com/forum/index.phpthere's also steam workshop mods, but these are easier to install and will not update and cause problems-unity 5 port coming soon to a steam store near you-a great way to get more people on your friends listcons:-difficult and way too complicated for new players who don't have any help or background understanding-the game's store page picture showcase is from the most earliest version of the game, 2014-creator is putting from the depths on hold so that he can make a new game, only tiny updates happen, like small block texture updates, but he will return maybe after a year or a half year-building takes a long time, including testing, updating designs-in order to make youtube videos like lathrix does, you need to edit a lot of the building out because it takes so long-in most multiplayer building games, it can be difficult to do co-op designs unless you and your friend(s) have the same designing process-it is difficult to play with players across the world, recommendation that you play with players in neighboing countries or your own country-early access, a lot of unfinished stuffother than that, this game is great to have in your library"
76561198079730609,Recommended,268650,17913464,"Posted: 6 September, 2015",all,Avius-Chan,"This is how this game works. You buy the game, watch the tutorial, get excited, build your first ship, first ship sinks, you go back to the drawing board, you make improvements, Ship works YAY, you get excited, you spawn a small enemy ship, you blow it to bits, you feel accomplished you spawn 2 small enemy ships you blow them to bits, you start to have faith in your design, so you spawn a bigger enemy, and guess what happens there, YOU get blown to bits, you cry, rage quit the game and go to sleep, after all you've been playing for 7 hours straight. During your sleep, you get a dream about a new stronger design, you either wake in the middle of the night with excitement or wait untill morning, anyways, you construct your new improved and mighty ship, you spawn the bigger ship that blew you to bits hopeing for revenge, 20 seconds later you're inches away from breaking your monitor as your ammo caches gets hit by a stray shell from his cannon and makes a majestic explosion. You ralise, armour is the solution, so you go back to the drawing board and make the most armoured ship you can, you release it in the water....it sinks, you keep trying and it keeps sinking....you're frustratd, insecure, you have lost faith in your designs, you think you cant play this game anymore, but it's too late you already played 20 hours of it in the first 2 days, you realise you cannot give up. You then open ol' trusty google and youtube you scour them for as much information as you can. 7 hours of research later and a few physics lessons from your old school book read on the way. You become a ship building expert, you then use your new found knowledge to design the ultimate boat to crush your fearsome enemy and then...... SUCCESS!! You have sunk the enemy ship. You feel good about yourself, go fap and go to sleep all happy feeling like a worthy engineer. You wake up next morning thinking ""Hey, I wanna try my luck with the campaign"" You start the campaign, remember you still have some left over confidence from that battle in the designer mode, first thing that happens in the campaign, you get attacked by a dingy you feel even more confident and actually for a second believe you can win this campaign. 20 mins later, you get attacked by the Deep Water Guard Crazy Chicken Armada. You look at that vessel in disbelief, cursing the day you bought this game (which is about 3 days ago) and the Crazy Chicken blows you and you fleet to smithereens....you rage quit and you rinse and repeat the above.11/10 would buy again."
