76561198258267261,Not Recommended,268650,28509854,"Posted: 21 December, 2016",all,The Hungry Thing,"TL;DR: You need to make a large time commitment and motivation to get anything done, but please read the entire review.Before you read this, this is a negative review because of the fact that while I would love this game, it has flaws that make it impractical for me.When first opening, there are no problems. The main GUI is simple to understand and easy to navigate, although grammatical errors appear every now and then. The main issues are with the steep learning curve and the fact that the tutorials don't really give you an idea of how to make a ship/airplane that fulfills all of the ""requirements"" that most set; It must be good looking, dangerous to the enemy, resource, fuel, and energy efficient, and have a practical purpose. It gives the building blocks, but lacks an explanation on how to put them together. I do understand, however, that games that ""hold your hand"" can quickly become annoying, but some early instruction would be nice.The learning curve is quite steep; it took me 10-15 hours to get a moderate grasp of most of the components and how they work. It can get frustrating when the tutorial doesn't explain the concept well enough for you to understand (the airplane ones were like this for me).Once past most of the tutorials, I hopped into designer, and, seeing people like Robbaz, Lathland, and Redstonize, I set about making a ship to beat them all! Then failed. One of the biggest challenges faced by the newcomers is the fact that you have to build your own ships from scratch, without any guides on the simple things like how to shape you hull and the best layout to organize things like ammo, engines, and mainframes, or a general idea of how much you'll need.IMPORTANT PART STARTINGThe time commitment is huge for From the Depths. It will take a considerable amount of time to build any decently performing ship. Battles can take a while, restocking and moving fleets takes time to learn and perform. All of your desings need prior thought to build; it is not a ""sit-down-during-lunch-and-play-for-5-minutes-game."" It will be easy (and almost required) to play for hours at a time, and for younger kids with ""technology time"" restrictions, it will be challenging. You will need to plan and plan and plan to make sure everything fits together nicely.Finallly, time for the gameplay. It is well put together, clean, pretty easy to understand, and gets harder as you progress. The killer: time. Yes, my biggest and (almost) only problem is time. If you have the time to spend, go for it. For the casual gamer, balancing a job, school, or time restraints placed by parents or schedules, this is problably no for you. If you have the motivation, then go for it, as the sucesses outweigh the troubles in the long run.IMPORTANT PART ENDED"
