,Recommended,268650,31597740,Posted: 6 May,all,"Solaire, Lord of Sunlight","This game is absolutely wonderful and well done. It is a voxel based ship/vehicle combat simulator. However, the campaign is what takes up most of my time as the author of this game singlehandedly built over 400 individual ship designs that over 6 factions actively use to kill you. I myself am a humble builder preferring a couple smaller effective airships or boats, but the limits in this game are astounding and the author plans to continually update this game even though he is working on a successor to this with an actual game company so support for this game will not stop.The community on reddit steam and elsewhere is very friendly and helpful and the game has a rudimentary multiplayer support for the campaign with no game breaking bugs. This game is hard to pick up at first I would 100% recommend turning the diffculty to easy and basicallly make yourself next to invincible while you pick apart enemy ship designs to learn their building designs and weaknesses.Even with the incredibly friendly and in-depth tutorial you will still have some issues fighting the campaign ships on normal difficulty(they are really well done).A con is a memory leak issue that happens if the game is open for hours at a time. Causes the game to stutter at 3 hours. He is working on a fix in the next update after his hiatus from this game( approximately 2 months away).perhaps another would be that the ships the creator designed are really god damn good. You need to cater your ships to their weaknesses but in all fairness this is a positive to me.The game has a somewhat realistic fuel efficiency and ballistic damage with different shell types, barrels, gun velocities. There is even a IAMS defense system as well as an offensive laser/railgun. All somewhat realistically modeled.  The biggest ship in the game is the Meteor and probably one of the hardest designs to fight one ship vs one ship. in game i belive it is 50000 m3. Its a flying saucer with an array of missiles and a giant laser that cut my flagship in half.) The ship is completely controlled with ingame modules however, you can use lua scripting to get a more precise control (I only use LUA for hover ships as it keeps them at a nice altitude while programming a couple purposeful kinks to dodge bullets. I can program LUA, but i found a design online that was much more well put together so i copied it.)You can be as hardcore as you want but sometimes cruising through on easy trying to beat the game with only 1 ship is somewhat casual fun."
