76561198023416519,Recommended,268650,17950560,"Posted: 8 September, 2015",all,Nitara,"Incredibly deep build-things-to-blow-things-up sandbox game.  Unique from other titles in this genre (but there are more and more solid, similar games, with different elements), boasting not only competetive play and casual sandbox play but also a number of preset scenarios to challenge your design, and a great big delicious campaign mode, which I've barely scratched (at >300* hours).You can tell I just enjoy blowin'♥♥♥♥♥♥up trying to get that perfectly balanced, ordinance-spewing, sleek, sexy war machine.  SO MUCH LOVE.* Update after many more hours of enjoyment: still fun as hell just figuring out more effective ways of blowin'♥♥♥♥♥♥up.  Still an amazing game with frequent updates, a lively community, and an absolutely incredible diversity of creative content.The updates are not to be understated.  Recent additions range from railguns and advanced cannons (which are custom built) with customizable ammo (in addition to missiles that have long been customizable) to a complete engine revamp to detection systems (more on that later) to a UI tweak that *finally* laid out block varieties logically (THANK YOU! YES) and this list will grow too lengthy, you get it.  They've also progressively added some pre-built components to help folks get started or simply save time - like several types of engines, which are now fairly involved in their creation from the prior 'more of these and these and these = best', as well as weapons and other components.  Oh, and particle cannons.  One of my favorite ways to say hello - with shiny blue lights of DOOOOM!Here's some more if you're not convinced.  How about different styles of play?  What's the most difficult playstyle to include in a game where destruction is the focus, besides diplomacy (which is also implemented, but I'm not experienced with)?Stealth.Well, guess what?  There are now robust detection mechanics in-game, including detection via optical camera, IR camera, laser, retroflection (seeing the glare of optical and laser detection systems), radar, sonar, and more - and counters to each.  Want to hide from radar - i.e. the simplest, most straightforward way of missles and craft finding targets?  Each type of block has a certain radar profile - everything functioning with precise physics - and by using both a slim profile design (think of a B-2 bomber) and passive detection systems, like passive radar (for above water targets), by staying below water and detecting via active or passive sonar (since radar can't detect subsurface targets), or even using a ""wireless snooper"" (which detects transmission between a vehicle's AI computer and components connected wirelessly, as opposed to physically block by block), you can effectively minimize your opponents' ability to detect your craft.  You might also do these, AND deploy radar bouoys to 'ping' your opponent remotely.  Of course, your opponent might pepper an area with sonar or radar buoys of their own to search you out; they may be able to detect your engines' heat signature via infrared or flat-out see you with a camera......you can see where this is going - this game has endless depth (har har) and is growing constantly.  It's absolutely worth every penny, and I'm saying this as someone who STILL hasn't gotten into the campaign, because I'm a bit crazy and have this problem where I say ""ok, I'm going to design a nice cheap ship to get my fleet started in the campaign.""  A few hours later - or ten, or fifteen - I have something 3x more expensive to build that can annihilate a weak enemy fleet in minutes that's about as stable as a cannister of compressed hydrogen over an open flame and handles like dung.  So you could say I'm still pretty new.  That said, I've just completed a reasonable little destroyer that just might work and looks pretty slick (and it doubles as a sub! not that I've managed to get the whole diving/submerging when needed automatically finished), so the next time I revisit this review, I may have some campaign experience under my belt!I have nothing bad to say about it, and I'm critical.  It doesn't feel at all incomplete.  Things are always reworked and added - part of a living development cycle - but nothing feels missing.  I do have a wishlist, though... automated control blocks (which already exist serving SO many roles, like deploying/releasing hot air balloons or controlling air pump bouyancy) would be even more awesome if they could enable/disable detectors.  I'd like to be able to switch off active detection and be able to ""go silent"" using passive systems only (think disabling active sonar when surfacing a sub, or disabling active radar at low altitude flight).  I'd also love to have AI connector 'wires' - effectively extended blocks of connectors ala beams.  Maybe have a version that's a little sturdier with only connectors on either end (an armored/insulated conduit, basically)."
