76561198138696287,Recommended,268650,34226338,Posted: 13 August,all,Papa Stalin,10/10
,Recommended,268650,12046705,"Posted: 10 September, 2014",all,Angrytiger,"From the first time you begin crafting your own vehicle -- varying from seagoing vessels, to aircraft, to spaceborne vehicles, with the promise of land-based vehicles on the way -- it's clear that From the Depths takes the mechanics of crafting your own personal vehicle to an extent that most other games haven't dared. Without naming any names, this isn't a game where you get predefined hulls with a drag-and-drop parts list to min/max stats; instead, you have to build the vehicle from the ground (or keel, as it were) up, making sure to provide it with an engine, an AI system that needs to be wired into the weaponry, and the weaponry itself. And even weapons are completely crafted -- the more powerful or accurate you want it to be, the more resources and room it takes up, forcing players to find the perfect balance between making their ultimate gun(s) or missile launcher(s) and being able to fit it on their hull.The lego-like simplicity of building your ultimate war machine is offset by a few pragmatic concerns you need to observe -- key above all is a physics system requiring balance as a mandatory part of design. Tempting though it may be to make your ship completely out of steel for maximum armor, it will also sink like a brick, maneuver like one, and cost an arm and a leg. And symmetry of design is necessary for the same reason -- making a spaceship that's got a Millennium Falcon-esque vibe to it will lead to tears when you realize that it has an off-center balance.Criticisms for this game, from my perspective, revolve mainly around a few important points. First of all is that, beyond the sandbox building, there isn't much to be seen from a gameplay perspective (YET, if this game's hype doesn't rapidly exceed the creators' abilities). The campaign, such as it is, is an ill-explained board game type strategy game, where you move your fleet around and capture resources. You drop into a fight against enemy ships/aircraft, defeat them, move on. Beyond forcing the player to maintain resource caps, it has no real sense of depth at this stage in development. The other is that, while in some extents the building is great, it falls flat in the departments of variety and (despite praising it before) complexity. There are all of 5 basic block types, and turrets have an unfortunate tendency to look the same, no matter the size, number of barrels, or parent vessel. And while it's neat to have to attach weapons to your AI's mainframe through 'wiring', said wiring comes in the form of specific connector blocks -- forcing you either to build turret mounts bigger and bulkier than you intended to protect these vulnerable pieces (without which your AI can't fire the weapons), or you leave them exposed to enemy counterbattery.How might these issues be corrected? I'm not even gonna play armchair dev and try to say, definitively, what the fixes might be, but I can offer ideas:1.) Allow research and/or 'backwards-engineering' in the campaign. Lock certain pieces (the 'extra' parts that can be attached to an engine to increase its capabilities, i.e. superchargers) and make it possible to either research their usage or capture the technology when fighting enemies. Ditto for varieties of blocks beyond wood.2.) Turn connector pieces into 'wired blocks', with armor available based on base material just like normal building blocks, and in exchange an escalating price scale.Is From the Depths worth it at this point in the cycle? Well, it depends on whether you really enjoy building stuff. If this is your cup of tea, you can sink hours into the 'game' as it stands at the moment. If you (like me) desire a balance between sandboxing and kicking over the castles in the sandbox a few minutes later, the game is far too underdeveloped at this stage... and anyone looking for an action-packed experience is in for a bit of regret."
