76561197970436838,Recommended,268650,12021665,"Posted: 7 September, 2014",all,aliengmr,"Think Space Engineers, but...different.That's the simplest way to describe this game. The concepts are ""roughly"" the same, but From the Depths (FTD) goes in an entirely unique direction. Most notably with AI.There's a bit of a learning curve, but its well worth it. If you like Space Engineers you should own this. As far as I can see this game in criminally overlooked. Its at an early stage, but there is a helluva lot of game here. There's story missions and even a sandbox campaign, assuming you can pull yourself away from the vehicle creator. There is quite a lot of stuff you can build too. Its really more than I want to get in to.Suffice to say that if this sort of ""sanbox block-building"" interests you, own it, simple as that, just own it.As for its early access development. Pretty sure this is a one man show (I think), so don't go expecting weekly updates. However, the developer does respond frequently and engages the community. Like I said there's a lot here already so its more than worth the price."
76561198014241544,Recommended,268650,12103608,"Posted: 14 September, 2014",all,wooaa,"Great game! I have spent nearly 30 hours on the game so far, and that is me just derping about in the builder menu! AI is good, although I have noticed that they always seem to shoot for the players robot, and with a bit of work that can be exploited, but that is me just nit picking as it is an alpha. Building in this game is very easy, once you get the hang of it. I was used to building games like Minecraft and Kerbal space program, so I was initially off put by the building interface. However, once I got the hang of it I could build rather complex boats with out too much work, it was that powerful. The ability to save chunks of craft, like turrets and engines you spent 7 minuets designing, then paste them later is an amazing tool that I have only seen in Kerbal Space program. My one real criticism is that this game, as befitting is complexity and depth, does have a bit of a learning cliff. Luckily there are good video tutorials online, including some made by the devs. I have seen betas and even full games that are less complete then this. And the fact that there have been 3 smallish but very useful updates in the last month,  makes this one of the best games of the year.TL:DR  amazing game once you get into it."
