,Recommended,268650,24552511,"Posted: 27 July, 2016",all,Fazzan,"A gem, if you like building vehicles. I tend to mainly build ships, but you can also build subs, planes, helicopters, floating fortresses etc.You have to balance weight, lift, resources and power.Made that ship too top heavy? It will roll over.Filled the ship with lead? It will sink.You design the ammo the guns use. Want penetration? Want it to explode after penetrating 3m of steel? Want HEAT capability? You can have all that and moreIf you like the designing ships (and things), you'll spend hours upon hours in the designer. I've spent more time in the designer than in the campaign.I recommend this game, even if you have trouble with logic and spatial awareness; You can train your brain to an extent."
76561198013132245,Recommended,268650,17619150,"Posted: 19 August, 2015",all,huminado,"After logging about 10 hours game time, mostly just designing BOATS THAT FLIP OVER AND SINK VERY EASILY, I finally started playing the campaign.This game seems to be the most detailed RTS concievable.  Build your units block by block if you want to.  Build your resource collecting block by block too.  Build engines and tinker how many cylinders, how many crankshaft sections, where to place carberators, more suerchargers or more local fuel tanks etc.  Listen as the torque capacity goes up and the RPMs go down!Warning: The learning curve is rather large.  There are still non-intuitive parts of the interface.  For example, if you try to put a gun together, you might have components that aren't contributing anything just because of where they are placed, and I'm still learning to master these nuances.  Looking at a block shows whether it's connected, but it doesn't glow or somehow make it more obvious at a glance - you have to double check.Same for engines - it's a balancing act swapping out a supercharger for a fuel tank to see if the power capacity goes up in unforseeable ways.  Maybe eventually this will all make sense (like an ""aha!  that's because there was only 1 carberator there and not 2!"") - but right now for me it's all very mysterious and fun.  :)Another Warning:The build mode also has a concept of what is being editted, which isn't clarified by the tutorials that I had gone through, so if you want to change a gun in the middle of changing the ship, I was scratching my head why it wouldn't let me place blocks for the longest time before it made sense.I'm sure I have not fathomed everything possible in this game, but it is meting out a great feeling of satisfaction discovering all it has to offer.--- FINAL WARNING ----The game really does move heavily in the direction of ""serious games"".  These are games which try to simulate real world problems.  You can program Lua scripts in FTD, and you may want to, if you have that sort of time at your disposal.  Personally, I start to wonder if I couldn't be spending my time better programming in the real world, rather than in the game....  your mileage may vary.  :)  Chin up!Also have a look at the very detailed models available in the workshop.  There are 1:1 ratio replicas of historical battleships and ...  lots more."
