76561198021662812,Recommended,268650,12392781,"Posted: 6 October, 2014",all,Nopkar,"What is it:From The Depths (abbreviated FTD in the future) conceptually is fairly simple. Create your own vehicles and wage war against other player's and/or AI controlled opponents in either scenario play, sandbox or a 'Grand Campaign' setting.This is where it gets interesting. Creating your vehicles isn't a monumental task by any means but it requires a deeper understanding of the mechanics than might be apparent at first glance. Engines are designed block by block and vary in power output and fuel usage. Weight of your vehicle plays a vital role as most engagments are sea/air based and you can't have a boat that bobs and weaves in the water, you'd never be able to hit anything!Basic learning curve is right around 5 hours with no handholding by the game itself. there are some pretty basic tutorials to get you going but by this time you should be able to make a small raft and make it move about with some simple guns on it.Novice learning begins about the 10 hour mark where you've probably completed your first custom cannon and missle arrays and can make a solid ship that doesn't flip over when making a hard turn in rough waves. From here its all about refinement. You won't know how good you are until you match up against some of the big AI ships in the game and even those can be dealt with in clever and inexpensive ways.Multiplayer is foreign to me. I haven't spent any time there yet in my 20+ hours and don't anticipate to do so in the near future.Singleplayer is a blast if yet unrefined. The planned updates are very promising and what the developer has already delivered on is well worth your $20 if you can stick with it, watch/read a couple of tutorials and enjoy figuring things out on your own. once your first completely AI driven ships moves to take out an enemy fleet and succeeds, you'll be hooked."
76561198068192340,Recommended,268650,12005657,"Posted: 6 September, 2014",all,Trigrhappy1,"Where do I even begin. Amazing game, From the RTS like perspective of the campaign mode, down to the very last detail of customization, this game has proven so far to be weeks if not moths of fun. It is challenging, rewarding and just plain addictive because of the level of creativity available to you. Not only is it well developed but the developers are constantly listening and helping on the game's forums. From the depths is sure to soon make its way to the top of the rising ""block construction"". Even now in it's alpha stages it is diverse, well done, and a blast to play with so much more to come considering this is the tip of the iceberg.In a 1 out of 10 rating I'd give it an 11."
76561198011961991,Recommended,268650,12671048,"Posted: 28 October, 2014",all,LunarCataphract,"I am not going to have this review be anything more than a review of the features I have experienced, namely the construction mode, piloting a boat and the controls in general. I'm going to start with the construction mode which I feel is the strongest part of the game. In the construction mode the controls are great, they work very well once you learn them which was annoying at start but once I learned what I was doing it got less irritating. There's a huge learning curve involved in this game but numerous online videos and ingame turtorials assist in this matter. My only real grievance with the construction mode is that forward, left, right and backwards are all relevant to the camera instead of being fixed. I personally do not consider this a weak point of the game mearly a different feature that appeals to different people depending upon who you are. The only final issue I have with the building mode is how you can'thave blocks levitate in mid air which I would have found very useful at it'd let me place down ""borders"" for my vehicle. One other issue I have with the game is the inability to move blocks around after you place them down or select more than one block at a time. To sum this pargraph up the building mod is good and has a very strong series of core mechanics, if with a difficult and often annoying learning curve as well as a few control issues and lack of helpful features here and there.The controls are great for piloting boats, not sure if they work for aeroplanes or the other vehicles as my personal lack of enjoyment with the game drove me off it before I got to that point, but when it comes to using turrets on rotating bases I found the only way I could decently aim was to stand on them which resulted in the turret being shot at an me getting knocked off, all the while I was being shot at. Personally I believe just removing the robot you played as would be easier for the game. When you're in the building mode this removal of the robot figure would simply place you as a disembodied camera. And when controlling vehciles being a disembodied camera wouldn't be useful I admit but a feature that ""locks"" you to the vehicle looking over it in a third person angle would be much easier. The final point I have to make regarding vehicle controls relates to the weapons and how they are only controlled if you're close to them, at least that was how the means of controlling them seemed. This system of only being able to control vehicles you're robot is standing on or close to sounds a little silly to me, after all you could easily get seperated from your vehicle due to incoming attacks.Over all I give From the Depths a personal 6/10 and I would recomended it if games of this nature are your cup of tea.+Creative and interesting concept.+Good mechanics are sound+Entertaining creating/building system-Intimidating learning curve-Feels unpolished in some areas-Weapons can be difficult to use."
