,Recommended,268650,18206523,"Posted: 26 September, 2015",all,Konoko,"This game has shown me that indie games can be absolutely awesome.Maybe I'm just a fast learner, but after a bit of messing about I'm already making great things. And I'm still just messing about in the designer, building stuff without constraints and such. Which is beyond fun by the way.And you see all those ridiculously fancy pants thingos in the screenshots? I just want you to know that while all these things are huge complex things which probably took whoever made em days on end painstakingly working everything out to the very last block, they're things you and I can make too. I get the odd sensation when I'm playing From the Depths that, yes, anything is possible.Unlike Minecraft, you've got way, way, waaaay more block shapes to choose from. There COULD be a few more shapes, but I'd say that'd just be going overboard, as it is I'm perfectly happy with it. I can make good looking boats, planes, helicopters, anything with what I've been given. In addition, you've got blocks that MOVE. As in, you point your mouse, a tiny spin block points to where your mouse is pointing.Unlike Garry's Mod, you have far more freedom with your weapons and materials. You don't have to hunt through the prop list to find exactly what you need, no, it's always right there in front of you, ready to be grabbed. And it's actually fun killing stuff. Obviously less physics based than Gmod, but, well, you're never really going to want to pull out a catapult to fight a boat when you could fire a cannon instead. Or a laser. Or a missile. It's fun killing stuff.And unlike Robocraft, this game is not actually♥♥♥♥♥♥ It's satisfying to kill things. When things lose blocks, they get blown off and float around for a while before disappearing. When you hit something with a really really big cannon, and it does a lot of damage, it really feels like it. There's no stupid block limits or anything. Unless you build something outside of the designer, which I have not done, since the designer gives me all I need: materials, and infinite space.Seriously, I know this looks like just another block-based building game, but it's the one that I've been waiting for (metaphorically). I wasn't expecting this even to be good. But it is. Just testing out my designs against enemy ships and planes is beyond exhilarating.If you've got $20 to spend, pick this game up. It's eyebrow-raisingly expensive for an indie game, but I'm saying it's well worth it at present."
,Not Recommended,268650,32140194,Posted: 2 June,all,۞Archer ✠,"This is a very good game, with alot of flawsyou cant build a massive detailed ship, because the game will be laggy as helldevelopers seems to be focusing on adding new stuff rather than fixing current lag issuesthe lack of shapes is kinda annoying, once you've build a medium-large design that looks nice, you probably will end up having major difficulties finishing it due to the lack of shape support, alot of the shapes just wont go neatly togheter....combat system is awesome, the variety of shells and missiles you can make makes it so fun, but the lag and the massive memory leakage really ruins the whole experiencei have a good pc with 32gb ram and 4.5ghz cpu and i get massive unplayable lags whenever i build anything big, or any major battles going oni love this game....but DONT GET IT, the lag in it just ruins the whole game, this can be fixed by the developers, but they rather add new contents rather than fix the problems.just like every other early access developers, make a game look good with alot of potential and ignore the fundmanental problems.Note to the developers:Stop making new items and features and fix the god damn lag and memory leak, this is more important than getting 50 new ways to make a ♥♥♥♥ing engine-.-'"
