76561197969782921,Recommended,268650,16553507,"Posted: 20 June, 2015",all,Flatline,"Very Brief Summary:Obligatory Minecraft reference - using blocks to build ships, planes, spacecraft, floating fortresses and really really really stupidly big guns that may or may not look rather phallic.Important Points:* The install size is very small, and the game is very stable and smooth. Loading times are minimal.* Your constructions will not wobble! Even as they're being shot to pieces, flying through the air or diving across the rolling waves, your creation will not wiggle and the parts will not look like the glue hasn't dried. Once you stick it together, it behaves like a proper, solid object.* The physics are robust. Whether you're ramming another warship, or just trying to make one that doesn't sink the moment you put it in the water, you can rely on the physics to make sense.* The combat is fantastic, whether you're manually aiming a weapon or leaving it up to AI modules that don't actually suck. Imagine Homeworld's colourful, trail-filled battles with Eve's general ship control, but with the added bonus of being able to walk around your ship and man the guns yourself.* You will spend too much time in this game, and neglect your wife/job/personal hygeine.Important features:* Comes with a huge list of pre-built vehicles, from tiny submarines to flying fortresses.* Weapons systems that can be customised in painstaking detail - if you want, you can build a cannon that runs the entire length of your ship, or an automated missile turret with 20 laser-guided missiles.* Single missions that act like challenges, which can be played with default vehicles or your own creations.* A campaign mode that's like one big RTS game, where all the units and structures can be designed by you.* The game is full of tooltips, documentation, visual examples and prefabricated components."
