76561198014157925,Recommended,268650,22235382,"Posted: 4 April, 2016",all,Golias,"From the depths is a fantastic idea with lot of potential that you can already experience in the Early Access.In this game you build a ship or aircraft (or a combination of both) using a combination of blocks (think minecraft) that you then use in a Campaign map to destroy other crafts, or in single event battles against others.The crucial element of this game is that each element of the build (engine, guns, missiles, hull) is itself built by blocks, that, depending on what you want to optimise, requires non-trivial choices of configurations. This reasoning applies to everything:* hulls: material and structure affects: attrition in water/air, area of exposure, weight vs armour.* guns: length of gun barrel, shell exit velocity, shell composition, reload time, barrel cool-out time, affects effectiveness of the shell on target, size, area of exposure to enemy fire.* missiles, mines and grenades, torpedo (pins, Infra-red detection, warhead size, etc.)* engine (cylinders, turbo-chargers, exhausts, etc.).For example, an engine can be built to be very heavy and efficient (in fuel consumption), but can also be lighter and less efficient, or optimised for low-RPM, or for high-RPM, and this depends solely on the blocks you choose, and how they are positioned in relation to each other.Finally, the combination of each of these pieces then makes the craft itself suitable for some things (e.g. a bomber, a battleship), but very unsuitable for others (a fighter, a submarine), and is therefore the combination of different designs that leads to total victory.Ah, and, of course, you then actually drive/fly the thing, or put an AI doing it for yourself. And there are a lot of other things (resources management and logistics, strategy and tactics in campaign), that I will not even touch here to simplify...It has the best ingame tutorial I ever seem (and I play computer games for more than 20 years), very good game mechanics, and lot of non-trivial decisions for the player.I strongly recommend this game.One of the major drawbacks of the current state of the game is FPS. Despite all the efforts from the developers, it is still in pretty bad shape, and I do hope that the code base on which this game is programmed allows to fix this outstanding issue."
