76561198141948560,Recommended,268650,27322161,"Posted: 24 November, 2016",all,The Paragon,"""From the Depths"" is a war sandbox, voxel-based builder.  It has a couple different campaigns that come with the game, but you'll mostly spend your time on Neter.  Here, you must build ships, planes, helicopters, tanks, fortresses, zeppelins, spaceships, and whatever you might need in order to conquer the eight factions that lie between you and all of Neter.Except it's not that simple.  Because the vessels you'll face aren't just some rummaged-together rafts with peashooters (althought some of the Deepwater Guard might actually apply to that statement).  They're great big battleships with thundering cannons.  They're planes that zip across the sky at super-sonic speeds.  They're airships that block out the sun.  They're satelites that can call down a hail of missiles from orbit.  They're thrustercrafts with more lasers than the local nightclub.  The learning curve is staggering, and the beginner will come into a new game with whatever they've managed to piece together to face the pirates, merchants, zealots, scientists, AIs, admirals, and aliens that are aimed against them.  And they'll probably lose.  But that's the fun part.  You lose, and you learn.  You build a better ship.  You win.  And then you lose to something even more powerful.  And then you build an even better ship.  And the cycle continues.  And you let it continue because it's oddly fun to tune your crafts, to make them balance in the water, or soar in the sky.  To make them bombard an enemy from afar from behind numerous shields and meters of armor plating, or ram them at high speeds with all the drills you can carry.It helps to have some free time, as you'll likely spend hours just working on a single craft, testing it in the vehicle designer before you actually bring it out in the campaign.  Heck, you might not even get into the campaign, and instead just keep building and building until you have crafted your own faction to rival all that might appose you.And you'll never stop.  The devs are active, updating the game on a regular basis, and there's a beta branch with even more frequent, if slightly more unstable, updates.  And the community is active, with a Workshop where people post modifications to the game, new vessels that they've built, or even new campaigns they've composed.  All new challenges to overcome.That's what From the Depths is about.  Building, learning, improving.  And it's why it might just be my favorite game."
