,Recommended,268650,21993131,"Posted: 22 March, 2016",all,Vis,"I do not often write reviews for games on Steam. It is not something I am inclined to do, given that most games do not entertain me enough that I feel justified in preaching about their good points, nor do they manage to bore or antagonize me so much that I must tell the world of the evils of their binary code nightmare.From The Depths is, as far as I can remember, the only game I have reviewed on Steam, and until something else as enrapturing floats along through the store, I am sure it will remain that way. The real joy of From the Depths is the engineering and building aspects. To take a concept, a simple outline of a deck shape, and then craft it over the course of several hours into a weapon of war is a joyous thing to those who love to tinker. Many hours I have spent refitting my various craft, the majority of them not spent in the grand strokes of deciding armament, propulsion, outline and armour. No, most of my time is frittered away testing. Endless testing, until I am absolutely satisfied, or completely frustrated at the performance of each system.And once your many hours of tinkering, designing, hairpulling and testing are over, you finally decide to put your craft through a live fire test. Unless you have been playing for a very long time, it will inevitably fail, or perform far below expectations during the test, usuallly because of a minor error in the design, or an enemy suited to counter what defenses you have in place.This is where From the Depths really differs from several 'Engineering' games. In From the Depths, I must consider bouyancy, drag on both the hull and superstructure, armour thickness from a variety of angles, armour spacing, and a myriad of other tiny details. It is in these minor details that the difference between a good and a great craft is made. Novel engineering is the name of the game, creating simple but efficient methods of doing things, testing out new ideas, scrapping bad ones, repurposing old ones. It is a game where my creativity matters far more than my ability to click on low resolution grass blocks.On a closing point, I think that the truly stand out feature of From the Depths is the relatively realistic damage model. Ships do not simply have a HP bar which indicates it's relative closeness to a complete and sudden loss of all structural integrity. The granularity of the damage model allows for several real life armouring techniques to be used, and in the event that they fail, makes for lovely looking wreckage.All in all, if you enjoy tinkering, building, or even just detailed damage modelling, then this is most definitely the game for you."
