76561198030515578,Recommended,268650,32649742,Posted: 22 June,all,Carolus Magnus,"In short:I can certainly recommend from the depths. I have sunk in a pletora of hours already, and I simply keep being drawn back in. In part due to the fact, that there are after these 850 hours of playing STILL many new things to learn and discover.Don't let the flashy ""early acces"" sign put you of! the game is currently very playable and very stable. It also stars far more content than many supposedly finished indie games.more elaborateThe main gropes the game currently struggles with are low FPS in big battles, but this issue is being adressed as we speak; and some balancing issues that are being steadily resolved by the devs while new content is being added. I've bought this game years ago, and currently it is a very different and far more feral beastie due to the continued dedication of the small dev team.the community is sometimes branded as being slighty acidic; but as always, if you are respectful in the forums and formulate your responses and questions properly I've found they are a very comely bunch of chaps (and ladies, undoubtedly). Many forum members are quick to offer concise answers to newbie questions, and are more than willing to aid newcomers and veterans both in resolving harder matters. there are many debates about game balance and techniques and the community is quite active.Of course, if you barge in shouting hell and damnation about your rediculously top heavy overgunned wooden ship capsizing all the time and taking it out on the game in cromagnon english, your reputation will be somewhat tarnished. But that is not unreasonable. Still, many forum members will be happy to point out gently that keels work wonders.The game has the player building vehicles to beat AI designs on a large RTS map, with maneuvers and resource gathering and many different and distinctly flavoured factions. there is one such campaign dedicated to tank warfare, which is ruddy fun; And a larger campaign dedicated to Naval, air and space and sub combat. Yes; There is a vast amount of possibilities.And those are only the official campaigns, as the community has free reign to design its own factions and maps at leisure!The armament, armour, and weapons available are staggering. there are missiles, multiple cannon variants, Particle accelator cannons and lasers and more. Each of these has a great amount of customizability to tweak to your personal needs and satisfaction. A great pleasure of mine is busting enemy AI designs with EMP weaponry, leaving them dead in the water, hulls intact (more scrap for me!).The game has difficulty customization options, quite a few graphical settings, and as many variable playstyles as you could dream up due to the above. Many layers of complexity can be switched of at player discretion, such as detection systems (think sonar, radar), and extended logistics and fleet upkeep.there is an active multiplayer scene, with a selection of deathmatch modes in which the players pit their designs against each other. There are also AI wave survival modes, and several others. You can also play the campaigns in coop mode with friends. I am not personally into the multiplayer community, but it's out there.There are often complaints from new players that the building mechanics and how everything works are not very transparent. there are tutorials, and many sources on the internet; but it remains a fact that it will take some time to get the ropes of this game. As it is, learning has been and still is a very rewarding process for me. Just do not expect to be able to tackle the campaign immediately, and take good care to make a few functioning designs in the sandbox vehicle constructor first! the youtube channel IreLan gaming has info on many systems, even if some of it is slightly out of date. A small amount of knowledge in the subjects of hydrodynamics and mechanics is advisable (archimedes' law, stability in the water, centers of mass and thrust). The game has a fairly accurate modeling ,so it pays to know how these things work in real life, even if at a ""for dummies"" level.If you are still in doubt; I would suggest checking out fellow Chaos Lord Lathlands from the depths series on youtube. His latest campaign playthrough reflects the current game state, and he should give you a good idea of what the game is like.Cheers from Belgium."
,Recommended,268650,32697457,Posted: 23 June,all,Slabo gaming,"I love this game, and the community is amazing"
76561198077906680,Recommended,268650,25556398,"Posted: 17 September, 2016",all,Yeedo,"+++++Thoroughly enjoyable gameplayCan keep you entertained for hundreds or even thousands of hours (just look at how many hours me and some other reviewers have clocked)Hundreds of blocks to build with, from sails and harpoons to ion thrusters and particle cannonsHuge variety of possible vehicles:Lots of different weapon types, many with incredible levels of customisability, for example the 'Advanced Custom Cannons' are built as a complex multiblock from ~15 different components, and then on top of that you can design the shells from scratch, with something like 30 different parts to choose fromPlenty of different propulsion systems to suit your needs, whatever they may bePretty much every major component from engines to AI controllers to weapon systems is a complex multiblock, giving you the power to adapt it to fit whatever requirements you may have; engines, for example can be built in infinitely many shapes and sizes and depending on which blocks you use (mainly carburettors vs fuel injectors) you can change its attributes, so it can be powerful, fuel-efficient or cool-runningYou can even program your vehicles and missiles with LuaThere are lots of cosmetic options as well, with several different main building blocks, including wood, metal, lightweight alloy and heavy armour, and in addition you have 100000000 different colours to choose fromThere are many difficulty options so you can make it as easy or as challenging as you likeThe devs (although most of the work is done by one guy, known henceforth as 'Nick') are, friendly, helpful and hard-working, and most importantly perhaps,communicate very regularly with the community; Nick has made, at the time of writing this, 13,706 posts on the forums, with many of these being bugfixing-relatedEDIT:Nick has been very quiet as of late during a Unity 5 portThe level of involvement with the community is demonstrated by most, if not all of the built-in designs (particularly Neter's factions' designs) being built by community members (although the distinction between devs and community is far from clear-cut)The community is also very friendly and helpful, much more so than any other gaming community I have seenThe game has been in active development for yearsIt seems fairly well-optimised, although it's not hard to make it laggy if you try, due to intensive physics calculations among other thingsThe sea and sky can look quite pretty, with realistic-looking waves, clouds and weather, and many different possible coloursThe particle effects now look beautifulThere is a highly-functional map editor so that you can make 'custom campaigns', with a huge number of options and customisation, including custom weather systemsThe built in campaigns, along with the story missions and 'adventure mode' provide thousands of hours of quality content, ranging from missions where you play as a member of one of Neter's factions to a realistic WW2 campaignVery reasonably priced considering the amount of work that has gone into thisLong and detailed in-game tutorials, supplemented by helpful threads on the forum by community members, and almost instant access to advice on the DiscordProbably lots of other stuff I forgot=====I hope you don't mind seagullsThe spelling and grammar is truly shockingThe AIs which control your vehicles are multipurpose for anything you build from space fighters to dreadnoughts, but they are pretty derpy and will happily shoot when a friendly ship is in the way and when using many vehicles on one team it is well known for its clusterfu.cking habitsThe spelling and grammar is truly shocking-----The terrain looks pretty 'meh' up close, since it is just one of a handful of textures tiled across the map (that said, it is fairly subtle, so it doesn't really give you eye-cancer)Multiplayer is very buggy and lacking in features, so I've personally never used it (and most people I know haven't either), and you'd be ill-advised to go in expecting a lively multiplayer experienceThe game can feel a little buggy in the wake of big updatesNick is mainly working on another game at the moment, but the other devs are still very much involved in FTD (although progress is slow, there is abigbalance and content update coming soon (TM)This game isHARD.It will take a long time to get past the steep learning curve, although there are plently of in-game tutorials and external guides to help you along the way. The main thing to be aware of is if you rush into the Neter campaign on higher difficulties the moment you have learned the controls, youwilllose, most likely spectacularly. Take it slowly, and you will find it much more rewarding.If you steer clear of games like Kerbal Space Program due to their high level of difficulty, or if you have very limited free time, this game may not be for you; it will take a long time to get good at this game, and you will suffer failure many times, but if you perservere it will be an experience like no other.Overall Score:10/10My all-time favourite game and a shining example of how game development should be done."
