76561197976543691,Recommended,268650,26243090,"Posted: 27 October, 2016",all,Rykmentti,"This game is a perfect time sink for people who like to use their imagination to build and bring their creations to reality and see how they fare against other players creations.In FTD you use building blocks to build almost anything you can imagine and by that, if you are thinking about ships you are right but the level of depth, customization and the game mechanics are way beyond of what you can probably imagine.For example if you are thinking about a turret on a ship, you cannot just ""build"" it. When you are building a turret, You have to decide the amount of loaders, clips, ammo inputs, coolers, recoil dampeners, mantlets, muzzles and so on the turret. This affects the rate of fire, accuracy, barrel cooldown, arc of fire and effective distance. After that you have to armour it too (so the turret you build doesn't explode when someone sneezes at it) which in turn will make the turret heavier making it turn more slowly.Think you're done? Next comes the shell itself. You can actually build real life shells in this game. (APDS and APCR (both Sabot rounds), APHE, HESH, Hollow Point, Squash, HEAT (shaped charge), Flak, EMP) and they actually behave like shells in real life. You can adjust the shell length, how much gunpowder goes into the shell, fuses, and order of the components put it. Also there is a really simple interface for seeing how the components you put in affect the overall performance of the shell, after that its just trial and testing to see how stuff really works. (How the shell reacts to light or heavy armour and shields short of)That said, this game has learning curve considered ""steep"" by most people. I myself thought I learned the basics in about one day then I thought the same thing 3 days later (when I actually ""think"" I learned them) and after about week I think I learned how the game mostly works, it all depends on how much time and effort you are willing to put into this game.This is really scratching the surface but I cannot possibly put everything into this ""small"" review here, so let me just put up couple things why you might want to play this game.1. Want to build up truly your ""own"" ships? Is it a submersible aircraft carrier? Flying battleship? Spaceship? Orbital Ion Cannon Satellite? Crab that chops ships in half? Suicidical nuclear armed sheeps? Almost anything is possible! (there is even a warp engine)2. Want to build replicas of your favorite things from fiction or real life?. Do you have a favorite game/movie/series/anime/real life ship,mecha or fighter you want to build? Build it and see how it fares in the game! You might be suprised of how well it works. What is even better that you can add even more stuff on your favorite thing if you so desire!3. Developers are very active on bugfixes and new content patches, also there is a very active gaming community on the From the Depths forums (both the steam forums and their own) that more than willing to play or help you with your problems.4. I honestly cannot think of many bad things about this game. Well the ""Campaigns"" are very subpar but the developers are focusing on the game mechanics and the building content itself before comitting to the campaigns (which is a good thing in my opinion). AI fighting by itself (moving mostly), is not perfected yet. Aiming, firing and target acquisition work almost perfectly and AI manages to circle around enemy ships but thats it. I use ready-made LUA code myself on all flying ships to control them which works very well.Oh wait there is one thing, one VERY bad thing about this game.After spending some time in this game, you start to think about what to build and how to improve your designs at school or work, where you should be focusing on your studies or working where you just stare at the emptiness while your mind is in overdrive.After that you forget to do all the assigned homework or courses themselves, next thing you notice that you should have gone to bed 6 hours ago and its 4 am in the morning! You could have sworn you just got out of the work.After that your boss calls you in the morning ""where the hell are you?!"" while you have been awake whole night thinking about how to perfect that one design and you in your sleep deprivation mutter ""my boat is sinking, my boat is capsizing, HOW CAN I GET TO NOT SINK OR CAPSIZE?!""Then after that, you find out you don't have a job and after that your teacher sends you an email that you have failed your classes due to being absent.After that, you reject real life altogether and just forget about everything before starting to playing this game ""for real""After that, you realize that living on the social welfare is not so bad.....After that.... you realize....This is...... life."
,Recommended,268650,26314224,"Posted: 30 October, 2016",all,Tolbryn,"If you are looking to build vehicles/war machines, this is the game for you. In comparison to other titles with the same style of gameplay, in from the depths there is much more variety to building a vehicle, but this variety comes with complexity and a big learning curve.If I wanted to describe building a vehicle in this game i would compare it to an animal. You have your different blocks which represent the different cells of the animal. These cells cant do much on their own, but if certain cells are put together in a certain way, they make up an organ which serves a specific purpose, for example the stomach processing food represents the engine processing food. All the different organs in a certain configuration make up the animal which finally represents the complete vehicle.So we can see where the complexity comes from. If we in the game forget to build an engine, then the vehicle doesnt have energy to move. Thats like an animal without the ability to digest food so it cant move. I think you get the idea.If you are willing to spent a lot of time in learning the game you can have tons of fun playing it."
