,Recommended,268650,28396109,"Posted: 15 December, 2016",all,Yuri Misaki,"The story of Yuri and FTDI remembered my early days in FTD as a fresh out from the rudementary and confusing tutorial... Struggling myself to understand every single important pieces to make things work. Going so far to mess up making my first Custom Cannon that ended up being a weak gun. I keep trying, trying to build things on my own.. But I coulden't do it because of this learning curve. It doesn't help to the fact that I'm used to another sandbox builder, Simpleplanes that I'm expecting it's going to be like that. But oh I was so wrong...With my computer fighting against me with threats of overheating... I cannot play this game anymore due to overheating.. Fast forward a one year and several months later.. I returned back, feeling fresh with a new rig at my disposal and possibly bored and has nothing to do at the moment. This is when I first witnessed the new changes. The CRAMs and the newer engine mechanics..and so many things... The tutorial got better than what I remember back then...which is good since I learned some things that I could ever hope myself to do.Armed with new knowlage in shipbuilding and stuff. I started to make my knowlage to good use. I started tearing apart preexisting ships to learn how it works.. One of the early ships I've worked on was that little sailbot with a lethal explosive cannon called ""Vanguard"". I've made many ships derived from it. It's not much, but it's a start from what I am already.Time has passed after my first fleet of Vanguard-based ships.. I started working on first airships of the DWG called Atlas. It wasn't fast or anything but I can see the potential for something big... So I equipped it with missile launchers and repositioned the guns from its underbelly. The upgrades was worth the trouble at least.After numerous updates and time in the game fiddling everything I could get my hands on right now. I started to come across some old designs that dates back in the CC era. Some of them were good enough for me that I wish the original makers would start updating it. But time has passed, there's no updates for those ships... Many things factor to that, it could be the original designers are lazy or retired FTD altogether. Or they might've lost their touch in constructing things and forgot how to design. But I cannot let those old designs be lost in the abyss.. Using my experience I've had in fiddling many constructables.I took myself to refit/modernize/overhault the old ships to make it work like originally before. Designs never die, if there's one who has the time to bring them on their former glory so they can see the sunrise again as they set sail.Um...the review...?Ah yes, I got sidetracked over my fond memories.There's many changes throughout the game's updates. From changing weapons to logistical overhaul in newer versions. My opinion about this unified resource which is the hot topic FTD at the moment is kind of a mixed bag. There's that one side of me that wanting it back due to complexity and thinking ahead what to do. And the other side of me that let it go uninterrupted. It's quite strange when you have a steam ship that eats up material that's composed of everything.. Surely the old system of resources might be preferable for steam engines, since you don't need to worry about losing resources if you keep the heat up. But then again... Bringing out your favorite ship, only to be stopped by the ever bothering insufficent metal. So you had to make wooden ships to get over that.I personally don't mind the changes, it's on the developer's will. And saves time to think about logistical problems of managing one type of resources on another as you worry about one kind of resource to worry about. This allows building ships less restictive and less stressful. But the cons for this system is that your precious unified material will get eaten by fuel refineries and high powered steam engines on localized resource.So if you don't like reading through my ramblings, maybe you should get the game like soon. Much better if you got it on sale as always. Don't let the learning curve stop you...once you get deep into the rabbit hole... You'll be addicted before you know it."
