,Recommended,268650,30920747,Posted: 3 April,all,6dwavenminer,"In many ways this is a two in one game, there's the vehicle design aspect and the RTS aspect.Vehicle design aspect:This part of the game is an engineers paradise with ability to customise and alter almost anything within a complex physics engine. That's right, if you place a backwards facing propeller at the rear of your ship, starboard of the centre of mass, the ship will not only go toward, but will also turn port. But don't worry if it seems too overwhelming at first, the game does a good job of allowing you to figure out one thing at a time with the assistance of a few tutorials.The combination of these two features, the customisability with the complexity of the physics engine really forces you to think and plan, but at the end you can come up with some truly spectacular designs in both form and function.But if you don't want to bother with that, don't worry there are plenty of brilliant design already available on the steam workshop.RTS aspect:The maps in FTD completely dwarf those of many other RTS's and game is essentially taking and defending resources zones while building, repairing and even resupplying your own military forces over land sea, air and even space.Now how you do this is completely up to you, remember you can fully customise your units, so if you want to Zerg rush your enemies with swarms of small cheap units, go ahead!Or perhaps you build to slowly build a giant mother-ship to destroy all in its way, then go do it!In the end, the game maybe hard to master, but with anything you do, you can do it your way!"
,Recommended,268650,26542921,"Posted: 11 November, 2016",all,Thomas Jefferson,"Before I give my rating, let me give you a slight background on my early experience with FtD:I watched a few game-play videos on YouTube, which depicted some fairly epic creations and battles. I then purchased it for my Brother, since it was on his wishlist. He played for only a few hours before he realized that he could not build anything that works. His statement to me about his experience was that it was way too complicated. Both of our interest stopped there for about 6 months.I then started to watch more videos of game-play. After watching Robbaz work on some of his creations, I finally bit the bullet and purchased it for myself. Right away, I spent a few hours going through the tutorials before I even opened the sandbox building mode. I can only say that without the tutorials, I would have given up like my Brother did. Even after completing all of the tutorials, I was still overwhelmed by the potential for complexity, especially with the weapons systems.Like all things in life, talent comes with experience. I eventually made some larger ships with complete weapons systems, and even a reasonably successful personal submarine. I have yet to create an aircraft or airship, but that will also come in time. The point is to not be discouraged by the complexity of building in this game. Not only can you download other creations in the workshop, it's very much worth spending the time to learn all the ins and outs of the building system.With that bit of info, I can definitely give this game a good review:The seemingly complex building system is actually a strong supporting feature of this game. It encourages the player to engineer something, and learn from the weakness of their creation.The game world can seem empty sometimes. I wish there was an actual trade system where you could trade and sell stuff with your allies.The AI in game is improving, but also still lacking. It will get better over time. The faction relations don't affect you much, except for who you're at war with.The ship AI systems are fairly new, and they're too simple to think much on their own (some ships crash into each other during battle, path-finding can be buggy, etc.). The weapon system AIs are okay. Their targeting system works, especially not that they have detection systems.Battles, once you understand how the system works, can be very satisfying. There isn't really any way to cheat, except for building a massive super-ship. If you lose, that's it. You have to rebuild your ships (from blueprints) and hope the enemy doesn't knock out your bases before you can recover.Development support is a little slow, but all the updates that I have seen have been fantastic. The small dev team listens to the community, while keeping to their original vision.The graphics aren't next gen, but they get a slight improvement every now and then. I'm not sure what the devs plans are for graphics, but it's more than playable. While this game is NOT about the graphics, I hope the devs put a little more effort to make it ""beautiful"", after it's feature-complete.Overall, this game is a 8.5/10. It's in development, so I expect that to be even higher down the road. While it is still in EA, you are very likely to get many hundreds of hours of enjoyment, especially as new features are introduced. I can say this for sure: If you like the idea of naval battles, the FtD is for you!"
